<HEADLINE>
<P>
IPPOLITO HANGS IN, HELIX BEATS EL CAPITAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICK HAZELTINE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LAKESIDE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The seventh-ranked El Capitan baseball team looked as if it had everything it 
would need Wednesday when it played host to No. 8 Helix in a Grossmont 3-A 
League baseball game. 
</P>
<P>
For starters, the Vaqueros had won six consecutive games and nine of their past 
10. El Capitan also had a team ERA of 1.87. 
</P>
<P>
For inspiration, the Vaqueros had center fielder Jeremy Ellis, who two weeks 
ago underwent an emergency appendectomy. 
</P>
<P>
But what El Capitan did not have on its side was pitcher Rob Ippolito and 
history. 
</P>
<P>
Ippolito struck out four of the last five batters he faced to lead Helix to a 
5-1 victory -- its 16th in the past 18 meetings between the two teams. 
</P>
<P>
The victory was doubly important for Helix (13-4, 3-0), which took over sole 
possession of first place over El Capitan (11-5, 2-1). First, the Highlanders 
came back after having their 21-game winning streak over Grossmont Conference 
teams halted by Grossmont, 12-1, Friday. And, perhaps more important, Ippolito 
pitched a strong sixth and seventh innings. 
</P>
<P>
The book on Ippolito was that he had been tiring after the fifth this season. 
</P>
<P>
"We knew he'd tire after five innings," said Steve Vickery, El Capitan coach. 
"I told the guys that it's a 21-out game, and we just have to hang in there." 
</P>
<P>
Jerry Schniepp, the Helix coach, was also keeping a close eye on his starter. 
</P>
<P>
"He'd kind of run on empty after the fifth," Schniepp said. "He was tired in 
the sixth and seventh, but he just sucked it up." 
</P>
<P>
With one out in the sixth and runners on first and second thanks to a walk and 
an error, Ippolito struck out the No. 4 and 5 batters to end the inning. 
</P>
<P>
In the seventh, Ippolito (6-1) struck out the first two batters and got Mike 
Farrell to pop up to the catcher to end the game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
