<HEADLINE>
<P>
TODAY AT THE AFI FESTIVAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS WILLMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Following are capsule reviews of today's screenings in the American Film 
Institute Los Angeles International Film Festival at the Cineplex Odeon Century 
Plaza Cinemas: 
</P>
<P>
'American Roulette' 
</P>
<P>
Great Britain, 1988, 102 minutes 
</P>
<P>
6:45 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 No doubt there's decent raw thriller material in the story of a deposed Latin 
American president finding himself on the run from death squads and foreign 
intelligence agents in London. This puffball of a movie squanders that premise, 
though, plying the Central American crisis merely for generic, 
sub-"Hitchcockian" romance and yuks. Writer-director Maurice Hatton strains 
credibility at every turn, having handsome hero-in-exile Andy Garcia run into 
KGB clowns, a sinister CIA operative, a WASPy love interest and any other fatal 
cliche in sight. Avoid.CHRIS WILLMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
