<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTPATIENT'S HEART LINKED TO DOCTORS BY REMOTE AID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From United Press International 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PENSACOLA, Fla. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 72-year-old man has become the first cardiac patient in the nation to take 
home a remote-control defibrillator, a device through which doctors can deliver 
a life-saving jolt of electricity by telephone, officials at Sacred Heart 
Hospital announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
The defibrillator, called MDphone, is linked to the hospital so that doctors 
can intervene in cases of cardiac arrest as well as monitor a patient's heart 
rate through a standard telephone hookup. The name of the patient was not 
released. 
</P>
</TEXT>
