<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTH BAY DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: COUNCIL OKS ASSAULT-GUN BAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Voting 4 to 1, the Lawndale City Council has given preliminary approval to an 
ordinance banning the sale of assault weapons. 
</P>
<P>
Mayor Sarann Kruse and Councilwoman Carol Norman had urged adoption of such a 
law shortly after a Stockton incident in which five schoolchildren were killed 
and 29 injured by a gunman with an AK-47 assault rifle. 
</P>
<P>
Councilman Harold E. Hofmann voted against the ban, citing his belief in the 
constitutional right to bear arms. 
</P>
<P>
The state Assembly has approved a bill banning the sale of most military-style 
assault weapons and severely restricting their possession by private citizens. 
That legislation is expected to be put to a state Senate vote today. If 
approved, it would supersede the Lawndale law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
