<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: HOMELESS SHELTER FILES FOR BANKRUPTCY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The San Fernando Valley's largest homeless shelter has filed for protection 
from its creditors in federal Bankruptcy Court in a last-ditch effort to stay 
open. 
</P>
<P>
"The shelter could not continue to survive without this," said Sydney Irmas, 
chairman of Los Angeles Family Housing Corp., the nonprofit organization that 
operates the 72-room North Hollywood shelter. "It had to have some relief from 
the mortgage payments . . . none had been paid in 1989." 
</P>
<P>
The shelter, a converted motel, filed under Chapter 11 of the federal 
Bankruptcy Code, freezing its $2.24 million in assets and preventing creditors 
from suing or foreclosing on its building. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
