FOR THE RECORD 
</P>
<P>
A caption on the digest page of Thursday's Westside edition incorrectly 
identified Igor Kotler, who was pictured speaking at a Passover event for 
recent emigres from the Soviet Union, as Yonaton Schultz. 
</P>
</CORRECTION>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Passover Is Special for Soviet Jews The Bureau of Jewish Education 
gathered recent Jewish emigres from the Soviet Union to share with them the 
traditions of Passover last Sunday. The eight-day commemoration of the flight 
of the Jews from Egypt, which started Wednesday evening, has special meaning 
for Jews who struggled to leave the Soviet Union. In learning the ritual for 
the two Seder meals, which are held on the first two nights of Passover, some 
of the immigrants munched dried fruit and nuts and heard a Russian Chabad 
cantor. Yonaton Schultz, bottom, discussed the traditional meals, during which 
portions of the Book of Exodus are read and foods symbolizing Jewish 
experiences are served with kosher wine. Schultz's young son nibbled on matzo 
while listening to his father. SANDRA TATUM / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
